<references/>

====Fortis and lenis====
The so-called voiceless and voiced obstruents are more properly {{w|fortis and lenis}}. Each member of a fortis&ndash;lenis pair is distinguished from the other by various articulatory and auditory features, but not consistently by voicing or lack of it.

In most dialects of English, the fortis (voiceless) stops and affricate {{IPAchar|/p t tʃ k/}} are always voiceless, and are aspirated ({{IPAchar|[pʰ tʰ tʃʰ kʰ]}}) at the beginning of a word and at the beginning of a stressed syllable: for example, RP ''today'' {{IPAchar|[tʰəˈdeɪ]}}, ''chain'' {{IPAchar|[tʃʰeɪn]}} and ''account'' {{IPAchar|[əˈkʰaʊnt]}}. Vowels and [[w:sonorant|sonorant]]s immediately preceding syllable final fortis obstruents are usually pronounced shorter than before lenis obstruents, as in [[bet|''b'''e'''t'']] vs. [[bed|''b'''e'''d'']] and [[bent|''be'''n'''t'']] vs. [[bend|''be'''n'''d'']]. This phenomenon is known as pre-fortis [[w:Clipping (phonetics)|clipping]].

The lenis (voiced) stops and affricate {{IPAchar|/b d dʒ ɡ/}} are always unaspirated. Lenis obstruents {{IPAchar|/b v ð d z dʒ ʒ ɡ/}} are often devoiced at the beginning or end of words, but are fully voiced between voiced vowels and sonorants.

The fortis&ndash;lenis distinction is neutralized in a few cases.

Initial consonant clusters consisting of {{IPAchar|/s/}} and a stop (as in {{m|en|spill}}, {{m|en|still}}, {{m|en|skill}}) are typically analyzed as having a fortis stop, which agrees with the spelling, but may equally well be analyzed as having a lenis stop (i.e., {{m|en||*sbill}}, {{m|en||*sdill}}, {{m|en||*sgill}}). The stop is both voiceless and unaspirated, and there is no additional phonetic feature that establishes it as either fortis or lenis.

In addition, American English has a sound change known as intervocalic alveolar {{w|flapping}}, in which {{IPAchar|/t d/}} are both pronounced as an alveolar flap {{IPAchar|[ɾ]}} between vowels or liquids and when not at the beginning of a stressed syllable, and {{IPAchar|/nt/}} between vowels may be pronounced as a nasalized alveolar flap, {{IPAchar|[ɾ̃]}}. The fortis stop {{IPAchar|/t/}} loses its distinctive voicelessness, and essentially becomes lenis. Flapping causes {{m|en|latter}} and {{m|en|ladder}} to both be pronounced as {{IPAchar|[ˈɫæɾɚ]}}, and causes {{m|en|winter}} to be pronounced as {{IPAchar|[ˈwɪɾ̃ɚ]}}, similar to {{m|en|winner}} {{IPAchar|[ˈwɪ̃nɚ]}}.

