==Middle English==

===Noun===
{{head|enm|noun}}

# {{alt form|enm|moneth}}

==English==
{{wikipedia|January}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|Januarie}}, {{m|enm|januari}}, re-latinised forms of {{cog|enm|Janevere}}, {{m|enm|Ieneuer}}, from {{der|en|xno|genever}}, from {{bor|en|la|iānuārius||(month) of [[Janus]]}}, perhaps from a {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₁ey-||to go|pos=a root}}. {{doublet|en|Gennaro}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈd͡ʒæn.j(ʊ.)ə.ɹi/}} ''or as US''
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|jănʹyo͞o-ĕr'ē}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈd͡ʒænjuˌɛɹi/|/ˈd͡ʒænjuˌæɹi/}}
* {{a|AU}} {{IPA|en|/ˈd͡ʒænjʉˌeːɹi/|/ˈd͡ʒænjəɹi/|/ˈd͡ʒænɹi/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-January.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{hyphenation|en|Jan|u|ary}}<ref>{{R:Hyphenation exception log}}</ref>

===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun|Januaries|Januarys}}

# The first [[month]] of the [[Gregorian calendar]], following the [[December]] of the previous year and preceding [[February]]. Abbreviation: '''[[Jan]]''' or '''[[Jan.]]'''
#: ''01/01/09'' : [[Thursday]], 1st '''January'''(,) 2009.
#: ''American style:'' [[Thursday]], '''January''' 1st, 2009.
# {{lb|en|rare}} {{given name|en|female|from=English}}.
#* '''2011''', Michael Schofield, ''January First''
#*: “Hi, '''January'''!” Lynn calls. “Happy birthday!”

