==English==

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/mɑːtʃ/}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|märch}}, {{IPA|en|/mɑɹtʃ/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-March.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ɑː(ɹ)tʃ}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|marchen}}, from {{der|en|frm|marcher|t=to march, walk}}, from {{der|en|fro|marchier|t=to stride, to march, to trample}}, from {{der|en|frk|*markōn|t=to mark, mark out, to press with the foot}}, from {{der|en|gem-pro|*markōną|t=area, region, edge, rim, border}}, akin to {{cog|fa|مرز|tr=marz}}, from {{der|en|ine-pro|*merǵ-|t=edge, boundary}}. Akin to {{cog|ang|mearc}}, {{m|ang|ġemearc|t=mark, boundary}}. Compare {{m|en|mark}}, from {{inh|en|ang|mearcian}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun}}

# A [[formal]], [[rhythmic]] way of [[walk]]ing, used especially by [[soldier]]s, [[band]]s and in [[ceremony|ceremonies]].
# A [[political]] [[rally]] or [[parade]]
#: {{syn|en|protest|parade|rally}}
# Any [[song]] in the [[genre]] of [[music]] written for marching (see [[w:March (music)|Wikipedia's article on this type of music]])
# Steady forward movement or progression.
#: {{ux|en|the '''march''' of time}}
#: {{syn|en|process|advancement|progression}}
# {{lb|en|[[euchre]]}} The feat of taking all the [[trick]]s of a [[hand]].

