==English==
{{wikipedia|lang=en}}

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|en|Aprill||obsolete}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|apprile}}, {{m|en|Aprill}}, re-Latinised from {{cog|enm|aueril}}, from {{der|en|fro|avrill}}, from {{der|en|la|Aprīlis||of the month of the goddess [[Venus]]}}, perhaps based on {{der|en|ett|𐌀𐌐𐌓𐌖}}, from {{der|en|grc|Ἀφροδίτη||Venus}}. Displaced native {{ncog|ang|ēastermōnaþ|lit=Easter month}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈeɪ.pɹɪl/|/ˈeɪ.pɹəl/}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|āʹprəl}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈeɪ.pɹəl/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-April.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Back ache-April.wav|Audio}}

===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun|Aprils}}

# The fourth [[month]] of the [[Gregorian calendar]], following [[March]] and preceding [[May]]. Abbreviation: '''[[Apr]]''' or '''[[Apr.]]'''
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1845|author=Robert Browning|title=Home-Thoughts From Abroad|passage=Oh, to be in England / Now that '''April'''’s there}}
#*{{quote-web|en|author=Steven Pifer|work=Five years after Crimea’s illegal annexation, the issue is no closer to resolution
|url=https://cisac.fsi.stanford.edu/news/five-years-after-crimea’s-illegal-annexation-issue-no-closer-resolution|publisher=The Center for International Security and Cooperation|date=18 March 2019|passage= The little green men were clearly professional soldiers by their bearing, carried Russian weapons, and wore Russian combat fatigues, but they had no identifying insignia. Vladimir Putin originally denied they were Russian soldiers; that '''April''', he confirmed they were.}}
#: {{syn|en|Eastermonth}}
# {{given name|en|female|from=English}}; used since early 20th century.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1947|author=Hilda Laurence|title=Death of a Doll|page=27|passage=I'm '''April''' Hooper. That sounds silly, the '''April''' part, but my mother was English and she always said there was nothing prettier than an English '''April'''.}}

