==English==
{{slim-wikipedia|May (disambiguation)}}

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|mā}}, {{IPA|en|/meɪ/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-May.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|en|eɪ}}

===Etymology 1===
From {{inh|en|enm|mowen}}, {{m|enm|mayen}}, {{m|enm|moȝen}}, {{m|enm|maȝen}}, from {{inh|en|ang|magan}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*magan}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*maganą}}, from {{inh|en|ine-pro|*megʰ-}}.

Cognate with {{cog|nl|mag||may|pos=first and third-person singular of {{m|nl|mogen||to be able to, be allowed to, may}}}}, {{cog|nds|mögen}}, {{cog|de|mag||like|pos=first and third-person singular of {{m|de|mögen||to like, want, require}}}}, {{cog|sv|må}}, {{cog|is|mega}}, {{m|is|megum}}. See also {{m|en|might}}.

====Verb====
{{en-verb|may|-|might|-|past_ptc2=mought|past_ptc2_qual=obsolete}}

# {{lb|en|obsolete|intransitive}} To be [[strong]]; to have power (over). {{defdate|8th–17th c.}}
# {{lb|en|obsolete|auxiliary}} To be [[able]]; [[can]]. {{defdate|8th–17th c.}}
#* {{RQ:Burton Melancholy|part=II|section=3|member=6|passage=But many times{{...}}we give way to passions we '''may''' resist and will not.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|poetic}} To be able to [[go]]. {{defdate|from 9th c.}}
