[[Category:enm:Days of the week]]

==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=thursday (disambiguation)|thursday}}
{{wikipedia|Week-day names}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰegʷʰ-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|Thursday}}, {{m|enm|Thuresday}}, from {{inh|en|ang|þursdæġ}}, {{m|ang|þurresdæġ||Thursday}}, possibly from a contraction of {{m|ang|þunresdæġ||Thursday|lit=[[Thor]]'s day}}, but more likely of {{der|en|gmq|-}} origin, from {{der|en|non|þórsdagr|þōrsdagr}} or Old {{der|en|da|þursdag|þūrsdag|Thursday}}; all from {{der|en|gmw-pro|*Þunras dag||day of the thunder god}}. Compare {{cog|fy|tongersdei}}, {{cog|nds-de|Dunnersdag}}, {{cog|nl|donderdag}}, {{cog|de|Donnerstag}}, {{cog|da|torsdag}}. More at {{l|en|thunder}}, {{l|en|day}}.

A calque of Latin ''{{l|la|diēs Iovis}} ({{l|la|diēs Jovis}})'', via an association ({{m|la|interpretātiō germānica}}) of the god [[Thor]] with the Roman god of thunder [[Jove]] (Jupiter).

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/ˈθɜːzdeɪ/|/ˈθɜːzdi/}}
* {{a|US}} {{IPA|en|/ˈθɝzdeɪ/|/ˈθɝzdi/}}
* {{a|NZ}} {{IPA|en|/ˈθɵːzdæe/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-Thursday.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-Thursday.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
:* {{rhymes|en|ɜː(ɹ)zdeɪ|ɜː(ɹ)zdi}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The '''fifth day''' of the [[week]] in many religious traditions, and the '''fourth day''' of the week in systems using the ISO 8601 norm; it follows [[Wednesday]] and precedes [[Friday]].
<!-- probably just an attributive use of the noun: # An appointment, person, or feeling associated with this day of the week.-->

