==Middle English==

===Alternative forms===
* {{alter|enm|Thuresday|Þursday|Thurysday}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|enm|ang|þūresdæġ}}, {{m|ang|þursdæġ}}, forms of {{m|ang|þunresdæġ}} influenced by [[Old Norse]] {{m|non|þórsdagr}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|enm|/ˈθuːr(i)zdɛi/|/ˈθur(i)zdɛi/}}

===Proper noun===
{{enm-proper noun}}

# Thursday

====Derived terms====
* {{l|enm|Schyre Thursday}}

====Descendants====
* {{desc|en|Thursday}}
* {{desc|sco|Fuirsday}}

===See also===
* {{list:days of the week/enm}}

[[Category:enm:Days of the week]]

==English==

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰegʷʰ-|*preyH-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|Friday}}, from {{inh|en|ang|frīġedæġ}}. Compound of {{m|ang|frīġe}} and {{m|ang|dæġ|t=day}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*Frījā dag}}, a calque of {{der|en|la|diēs Veneris}}, via an association ({{m|la|interpretātiō germānica}}) of the goddess [[Frigg]] with the Roman goddess of love [[Venus]].

Compare {{cog|fy|freed}}, {{cog|nds-de|Freedag}}, {{m|nds-de|Friedag}}, {{cog|nl|vrijdag}}, {{cog|de|Freitag}}, {{cog|da|fredag}}.
{{cog|non|Frigg}} (genitive {{m|no|Friggjar}}), {{cog|osx|Fri}}, and {{cog|ang|Frig}} are derived from {{cog|gem-pro|*Frijjō}}. Frigg is cognate with {{cog|sa|प्रिया|tr=priyā́|t=wife}}. The root also appears in {{cog|osx|fri|t=beloved lady}}; in {{cog|sv|fria}}, in {{cog|da|-}} and {{cog|no|-}} as {{m|da|fri|t=to propose for marriage}}; a related meaning exists in Icelandic as {{m|is|frjá|t=to love}} and similarly in {{cog|nl|vrijen|t=to make love (to have sex)}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈfɹaɪdeɪ/|/ˈfɹaɪdi/}}
* {{enPR|frīʹdā|frīʹdē}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-Friday.ogg|Audio (GA)}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-Friday.ogg|Audio (RP)}}
* {{rhymes|en|aɪdeɪ|aɪdi}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The '''sixth day''' of the [[week]] in many religious traditions, and the '''fifth day''' of the week in systems using the [[w:ISO 8601|ISO 8601]] norm; the [[Muslim]] [[Sabbath]]; it follows [[Thursday]] and precedes [[Saturday]].
<!--probably just an attributive form of the noun: #An appointment, person (like Man Friday in ''Robinson Crusoe''), or feeling associated with this day of the week.-->

