==English==
{{wikipedia|dab=sunday (disambiguation)|sunday}}
{{wikipedia|Week-day names}}

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dʰegʷʰ-}}
From {{inh|en|enm|sunnenday}} from {{inh|en|ang|sunnandæġ||day of the sun}}, from {{m|ang|sunne||sun}}, + {{m|ang|dæġ||day}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*sunnōn dag}}, as a translation ({{m|la|interpretātiō germānica}}) of {{der|en|la|diēs Sōlis}}; declared the "venerable day of the sun" by Roman Emperor [[w:Constantine|Constantine]] on March 7, 321 {{C.E.}}.

Compare {{cog|stq|Sundai||Sunday}}, {{cog|nds-de|Sünndag}}, {{cog|nl|zondag}}, West {{cog|fy|snein}}, {{cog|de|Sonntag}}, {{cog|da|søndag}}.

===Pronunciation===

* {{IPA|en|/ˈsʌndeɪ/|/ˈsʌndi/}}
* {{enPR|sŭnʹdā|sŭnʹdē}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-Sunday.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|En-uk-Sunday.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ʌndeɪ}}, {{rhymes|en|ʌndi}}
* {{homophones|en|sundae}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# The first day of the [[week]] in many religious traditions, and the seventh day of the week in systems using the [[w:ISO 8601|ISO 8601]] standard; the [[Christian]] [[Sabbath]]; the [[Lord's Day]]; it follows [[Saturday]] and precedes [[Monday]].
#* {{quote-journal
|en
|date=June 19, 2012
|author=Phil McNulty
|title=England 1-0 Ukraine
|work=BBC Sport
|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/18181971
|page=
|passage=And after missing a simple header in the first half, the Manchester United striker ensured England topped Group D to set up a quarter-final meeting with Italy in Kiev on '''Sunday'''.}}
# {{lb|en|informal}} A [[newspaper]] published on Sunday.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1974|author=John le Carré|title=Tinker Tailor Soldier Spy|passage=I gave him the switchboard with my love, went down to the Savoy for breakfast and read the '''Sundays'''.}}
# {{lb|en|informal}} A [[comic strip]] published in a Sunday newspaper.
#* '''2017''', Mark Arnold, ''Pocket Full of Dennis the Menace''
#*: It just wasn't his thing, although he did beautiful '''Sundays''' for however long he did them. So as soon as he could, he hired someone to do the '''Sundays'''. Karen and I would do some dailies, but we were the Sunday artists.

