===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} The [[art]] or [[craft#Noun|craft]] of [[compile|compiling]], [[write|writing]], and [[edit#Verb|editing]] [[dictionary|dictionaries]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=Craftsman, Feb. 22 &#91;[[Julian calendar]]&#93;. Nº 451.|editor=Sylvanus Urban [pseudonym; {{w|Edward Cave}}]|magazine=[[w:The Gentleman's Magazine|The Gentleman’s Magazine, and Historical Chronicle]]|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by}} Edward Cave,{{nb...|at St John’s Gate.}}|date={{J2G|22 February 1735}}|year_published=February 1735|volume=V|page=85|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=p1U3AAAAYAAJ&pg=PA85|column=1|oclc=192374019|passage=[T]here are ſeveral Species of Writing, in which a proper Degree of ''Hebetude'' is abſolutely neceſſary, as well as in other profeſſions; such as '''''Lexicography''''', ''Index-making'', and the like; [...]}}
#* {{RQ:Johnson Dictionary|chapter=Preface|url=https://archive.org/details/b30451541_0001/page/n14/mode/1up|passage=And ſuch is the fate of hapleſs '''lexicography''', that not only darkneſs, but light, impedes and diſtreſſes it; things may be not only too little, but too much known, to be happily illuſtrated.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:John Philpot Curran|[John Philpot] Curran]], defence counsel|chapter=612. Trial of James Weldon for High Treason,{{nb...|before the Court Holden under a Commission of Oyer and Terminer and General Gaol Delivery in and for the County of the City of Dublin, in the Kingdom of Ireland, on Monday December 21st, and Tuesday December 22nd: 36 George III. A.D. 1795.}}|editor={{w|Thomas Jones Howell}}|title=[[w:William Cobbett|Cobbett]]’s Complete Collection of State Trials and Proceedings for High Treason and Other Crimes and Misdemeanors{{nb...|from the Earliest Period to the Year 1783, with Notes and Other Illustrations: Compiled by T. B. Howell, Esq. F.R.S. F.S.A. and Continued from the Year 1783 to the Present Time: by Thomas Howell Jones, Esq.}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed by T[homas] C[urson] Hansard, Peterborough-Court, Fleet-Street: for}} [[w:Longman|Longman, Hurst, Rees, Orme, and Brown]]; [''et al.'']|date=22 December 1795|year_published=1819|volume=XXVI|column=267|columnurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=K7dCAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA267|oclc=712066713|passage=Let me warn you, therefore, against that fallacious '''lexicography''' which forms new words, that undergoing the examination of political slander or intemperate zeal, are considered as having a known acception.—What is the word?—A word that should be discarded, when it is sought to affix to it another meaning than that which it bears in the cases where it is used.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Henry Neuman|chapter=Preface|chapterurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=9o04AAAAYAAJ&pg=PP9|title=A New Dictionary of the Spanish and English Languages; {{...|wherein the Words are Explained Agreeable to Their Different Meanings, and a Great Variety of Terms Relating to the Arts, Sciences, Trade, and Navigation, Carefully Elucidated. Compiled from the Best Authorities, by Henry Neuman.}} In Two Parts|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for}} Vernor and Hood,{{nb...|J[ohn] Sewell, Cuthell and Martin, J. Walker, T[homas] Boosey, Lackington, Allen and Co., R. Lea, Otridge and Son, Ogilvy and Son, and J. Nunn; by T. Maiden, Sherbourne-Lane, Lombard-Street.}}|year=1802|volume_plain=1st part (The Spanish before the English)|oclc=1121491003|passage=[...] I have not only availed myſelf of all the Aſſiſtance which more ancient Sources of Spaniſh '''Lexicography''' could afford, but alſo had particular Recourſe to the Dictionary published at Madrid in 1797 and 1798, [...]}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Ying Hing Soo|chapter=Book Second|translator=Charles Fried. Neumann [''i.e.'', {{w|Karl Friedrich Neumann}}]|title=History of the Pirates who Infested the China Sea, from 1807 to 1810.{{nb...|Translated from the Chinese Original, with Notes and Illustrations}}|location=London|publisher={{...|Printed for the}} [[w:Royal Asiatic Society of Great Britain and Ireland#Oriental Translation Fund of Great Britain and Ireland|Oriental Translation Fund]],{{nb...|and sold by J[ohn] Murray, Albemarle Street; Parbury, Allen, & Co., Leadenhall Street; Thacker & Co., Calcutta; Treuttel & Würtz, Paris; and E. Fleischer, Leipsig}}|year=1831|section=footnote|page=54|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=8aUCAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA54|oclc=250438210|passage=There exist different forms of this character, but I think we should not presume to make an etymology of a Chinese character without being authorized by the [[w:Shuowen Jiezi|Shwǒ wǎn]], the oldest and most genuine source of Chinese '''lexicography'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=A[nthony] P[aul] Cowie|chapter=The Role of the Computer in Learner Lexicography|title=English Dictionaries for Foreign Learners: A History|location=Oxford, Oxfordshire|publisher=[[w:Oxford University Press|Clarendon Press]]|year=1999|section=section 4.1 (Introduction)|page=118|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=WRHzbsSjm0YC&pg=PA118|isbn=978-0-19-823506-4|passage=Without doubt, the most important single development in learner '''lexicography''' from the mid-1970s onwards has been the steadily increasing involvement of the computer at all stages of the dictionary-making process, from data gathering and analysis at one end, to compilation, production, and revision at the other.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Amy Chi|chapter=Researching Pedagogical Lexicography|editor=Howard Jackson|title=The Bloomsbury Companion to Lexicography|series=Bloomsbury Companions|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher=Bloomsbury Academic, {{w|Bloomsbury Publishing}}|year=2013|page=165|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=09JBAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA165|isbn=978-1-4725-4187-1|passage=A dictionary, as an art and craft of '''lexicography''', has always been closely associated with the notion of pedagogy.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable|linguistics}} The [[scholarly]] [[discipline#Noun|discipline]] of [[analyse|analysing]] and [[describe|describing]] the [[semantic]], [[syntagmatic]] and [[paradigmatic]] [[relationship]]s within the [[lexicon]] ([[vocabulary]]) of a [[language]] and [[develop]]ing [[theory|theories]] of dictionary [[component]]s and [[structure#Noun|structures]] [[link#Verb|linking]] the [[data]] in dictionaries.
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Moses Stuart|authorlink=Moses Stuart|chapter=Changes of Consonants|title=A Grammar of the Hebrew Language|edition=3rd|location=Andover, Mass.|publisher=Flagg & Gould|year=1828|section=part II (Changes and Peculiarities of Consonants and Verbs), §&nbsp;105|page=51|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=zyItAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA51|oclc=1036194|passage=But changes of this nature belong to '''''lexicography''''', as they do not affect the grammatical forms of words.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Geo. Benedict Winer [''i.e.'', {{w|Georg Benedikt Winer}}]|chapter=§&nbsp;4. Grammatical Character of the N.T. Diction.|translators=J. H Agnew and O. G. Ebbeke|title=A Grammar of the Idioms of the Greek Language of the New Testament|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|publisher=Herman Hooker,{{nb...|corner of Chesnut and 5th Street.}}|year=1840|section=part I|page=37|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=c7JNAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA37|oclc=982205048|passage=What the history of language in general teaches, that in course of time, there is less change in form than signification, in grammar than '''lexicography''', is true of the Greek.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Wilhelm Freund|authorlink=Wilhelm Freund|title=Article IV. Principles of Latin Lexicography.|translator=[[w:Theodore Dwight Woolsey|T[heodore] D[wight] Woolsey]]|editors=[[w:Bela Bates Edwards|B[ela] B[ates] Edwards]] and [[w:Edwards Amasa Park|E[dwards] A[masa] Park]]|journal=[[w:Bibliotheca Sacra|Bibliotheca Sacra and Theological Review]]|location=New York, N.Y.; London|publisher=[[w:Wiley (publisher)|Wiley & Putnam]]; Andover, Mass.: Allen, Morrill and Wardwell|month=February|year=1845|volume=II|issue=V|section=section I (Of the Idea and Elements of Latin Lexicography), §&nbsp;1|page=80|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=9uEWAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA80|oclc=6052689|passage=If '''Lexicography''' in general is that science whose task it is to set forth the nature of every single word of a language through all the periods of its existence, it is the task of Latin '''lexicography''' in particular to set forth the nature of every single word of the Latin language, as it makes itself known in all the periods of the existence of that language; or more succinctly expressed, it is the object of Latin '''lexicography''' to give the history of every single word of the Latin language.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=C. J. Ball|title=A Study in Biblical Philology|journal=Proceedings of the Society of Biblical Archæology|location=London|publisher={{w|Society of Biblical Archaeology}}|date=13 December 1911|volume=XXXIII|issue=CCXLIX|page=13|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=qQsaAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA13|oclc=1113492364|passage=[T]he philologist may well refuse to accept a body of triliteral roots, developed on a highly artificial and uniform plan, as the ultimate fact in Semitic '''lexicography'''.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Howard Jackson|chapter=Criticising Dictionaries|title=Lexicography: An Introduction|location=London; New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Routledge}}|year=2002|page=173|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=iQZK1NvRSMAC&pg=PA173|isbn=978-0-415-23172-5|passage=Academic '''lexicography''', or 'metalexicography', as pursued in university departments of English or Linguistics, is concerned not primarily with the compiling of dictionaries&nbsp;– though academics may be involved in this, as consultants, for example&nbsp;– but with researching and teaching about the whole business of making dictionaries: their history, their typology, their structures, their users, and so on [...].}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A dictionary, a [[lexicon]], a [[wordbook]].
#* {{quote-journal|en|author={{w|Joseph Story}}, Associate Judge of the [[w:Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]]|author2=William P. Mason, reporter|title=United States ''vs.'' an Open Boat and Lading|journal=Reports of Cases Argued and Determined in the Circuit Court of the United States, for the First Circuit|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=Hilliard, Gray, Little, and Wilkins|month=October|year=1828|year_published=1831|volume=V|page=134|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=zyE8AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA134|oclc=1013340480|passage=There can be no doubt, that in a general sense a ''boat'' is a ''vessel'', for it is "a vehicle in which men or goods are carried on the water," which is one of the definitions of a ''vessel'' given in our '''lexicographies'''; [...]}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|title=A Bag of Wind|magazine=[[w:Putnam's Magazine|Putnam’s Monthly. A Magazine of Literature, Science, and Art]]|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher=Dix & Edwards,{{nb...|10 Park Place.}}; London: [[w:Sampson Low|Sampson Low, Son & Co.]]|month=March|year=1855|volume=V|issue=XXVII|page=251|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=Nlw3AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA251|column=1|oclc=221113463|passage="Air put in motion" is the brief description of the wind in '''lexicographies'''; but what a contrast in quality according to its direction; [...]}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=Christopher Leigh Connery|chapter=Textual Authority and Textual Practice|title=The Empire of the Text: Writing and Authority in Early Imperial China|location=Lanham, Md.; Oxford, Oxfordshire|publisher=[[w:Rowman & Littlefield|Rowman & Littlefield Publishers]]|year=1998|page=37|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=MqeAvvCGlCEC&pg=PA37|isbn=978-0-8476-8738-1|passage=The earliest examples of dictionaries or '''lexicographies''' in nearly any culture serve more to regularize and standardize the lexicon than to list or inventory it, and as such would tend to take as their object textual rather than spoken language.}}

