==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|enm|sinonyme}}, from {{der|en|la|synōnymum}}, from {{der|en|grc|συνώνυμον}}, neuter singular form of {{m|grc|συνώνυμος||synonymous}}, from {{m|grc|σύν||with}} + {{m|grc|ὄνομα||name}}. Equivalent to {{confix|en|syn|onym}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{enPR|sĭn'ənĭm}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈsɪnənɪm/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-synonym.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}

# {{lb|en|semantics|strictly}} A [[word]] whose [[meaning]] is the same as that of another word.
#: {{syn|en|equivalent|poecilonym}}
#: {{ant|en|antonym|opposite}}
# {{lb|en|semantics|loosely}} A [[word]] or [[phrase]] with a [[meaning]] that is the same as, or very similar to, another word or phrase.
#: {{syn|en|metonym}}
#: {{ux|en|“Happy” is a '''synonym''' of “glad”.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|passage=The proportion of English words that have an exact '''synonym''' is small.|author=William T. Parry, Edward A. Hacker|title=Aristotelian Logic|year=1991|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=rJceFowdGEAC}}
# {{lb|en|zoology}} Any of the formal names for a taxon, including the [[valid name]] (i.e. the [[senior synonym]]).
# {{lb|en|taxonomy|botany}} Any name for a taxon, usually a validly published, formally accepted one, but often also an unpublished name.
# {{lb|en|databases}} An alternative (often shorter) [[name]] defined for an [[object]] in a [[database]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2011|author=Paul Nielsen, Uttam Parui|title=Microsoft SQL Server 2008 Bible|passage='''Synonyms''' are part of the SQL standard and are used frequently by Oracle DBAs. Note that Oracle includes both private and public synonyms.}}

