==English==

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|fr|sémantique}}, displacing earlier {{m|en|semasiology}}. From {{bor|fr|grc|σημαντικός}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/sɪˈmæntɪks/}}
* {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-semantics.wav |Audio (UK)}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|-}}

# {{lb|en|linguistics}} A branch of [[linguistics]] studying the [[meaning]] of words. {{defdate|1893}}
#: {{ux|en|'''Semantics''' is a foundation of lexicography.}}
# The study of the relationship between words and their meanings.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2006|author=Patrick Blackburn, Johan Bos, and Kristina Striegnitz|url=http://www.learnprolognow.org/lpnpage.php?pagetype=html&pageid=lpn-htmlse32|title=Learn Prolog Now!|section=section 8.1|passage=In fact, nowadays a lot is known about the '''semantics''' of natural languages, and it is surprisingly easy to build semantic representations which partially capture the meaning of sentences or even entire discourses.}}
# The individual meanings of words, as opposed to the overall meaning of a passage.
#: {{ux|en|The '''semantics''' of the terms used are debatable.}}
#: {{ux|en|The '''semantics''' of a single preposition is a dissertation in itself.}}
# {{lb|en|computer science}} The meaning of computer language constructs, in contrast to their form or [[syntax]].
#: {{ux|en|file sharing and locking '''semantics'''}}

