{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
{{calque|en|fr|faux-ami}}, from the longer phrase {{m|fr||faux amis du traducteur|t=false friends of a translator}}, first used by Maxime Kœssler and Jules Derocquigny in 1928 in their book ''{{lang|fr|Les Faux Amis ou les trahisons du vocabulaire anglais}}'' (''False Friends, or the Pitfalls of the English Vocabulary'').<ref>{{cite-book|editors=Mark Aronoff, Janie Rees-Miller|title=The Handbook of Linguistics|publisher=Blackwell Publishers|date=2001|author=Christoph Gutknecht|chapter=Translation|p=698}}</ref>

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˌfɒls ˈfɹɛnd/|/ˌfɔːls ˈfɹɛnd/}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|en|/ˌfɔls ˈfɹɛnd/|/ˌfɑls ˈfɹɛnd/}}
* {{audio|en|en-us-false friend.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{audio|en|en-au-false friend.ogg|Audio (AU)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun}}
{{examples|examples=
* The Spanish ''{{m|es|embarazado||pregnant}}'' and English {{m|en|embarrassed}}.
* The Chinese {{zh-m|手紙|tr=shǒuzhǐ|gloss=toilet paper}} and Japanese {{m|ja|手紙||letter}}, both of which are composed of the same characters.
* The Italian {{m|it|triviale||vulgar}} and English {{m|en|trivial}}. The two words are cognate through the Latin root {{m|la|trivium||crossroads}}.
}}

# {{lb|en|linguistics|translation studies|lexicography}} A [[word]] in a language that bears a [[deceptive]] resemblance to a word in another language but in fact has a different meaning.
#: {{ux|en|A word and its '''false friend''' may well be etymologically related: in such cases semantic shifts have made them drift apart.}}
#: {{syn|en|faux ami}}
# {{&lit|en|false|friend}}

