===Noun===
{{wikipedia|dab=craft (disambiguation)|craft}}
{{en-noun|~|craft|s}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable|obsolete}} [[strength|Strength]]; [[power]]; [[might]]; [[force]] {{defdate|9th century}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|William Bonde}}|title=Pylgrimage of Perfection|year=1526|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=OEHzMgEACAAJ&dq=Pylgrimage+of+Perfection+1526&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwji3NyNp9jcAhXFDZoKHT-zCmcQ6AEIKTAA|passage=By the '''craft''' of nature.}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[intellectual|Intellectual]] power; [[skill]]; [[art]].
## [[ability|Ability]], [[skilfulness]], especially skill in making [[plan]]s and carrying them into [[execution]]; [[dexterity]] in [[manage|managing]] affairs, [[adroitness]], practical [[cunning]]; [[ingenuity]] in [[construct]]ing, dexterity {{defdate|9th century}}.
##* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Geoffrey Chaucer}}|title=Parlement of Foules|year=c. 1381|passage=The lyf so short, the '''craft''' so longe to lerne […]}}
##* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|George Grote}}|title=A history of Greece|year=1846|passage=The Cyclôpes were Brontês, Steropês, and Argês,—formidable persons, equally distinguished for strength and for manual '''craft''' […]}}
##* {{quote-journal
|en
|date=11 June 2016
|author=Phil McNulty
|title=England 1-1 Russia
|work=BBC Sport
|url=http://www.bbc.com/sport/football/36450648
|page=
|passage=England should have had enough against a very ordinary Russia to complete the job but Rooney's removal robbed them of his '''craft''' and guidance and now increases the pressure on Thursday's meeting with Wales in Lens.}}
## [[cunning|Cunning]], art, skill, or dexterity applied to [[bad]] purposes; [[artifice]]; [[guile]]; [[subtlety]]; [[shrewdness]] as [[demonstrate]]d by being skilled in [[deception]] {{defdate|13th century}}.
##* '''1611''', {{w|Bible}} (King James), {{w|Gospel of Mark|Mark}} xiv.1:
##*: The chief priests and the scribes sought how they might take him by '''craft''', and put him to death.
##* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Thomas Hobbes}}|title=Leviathan, or the Matter, form, and power of a Commonwealth ecclesiastical and civil|year=1651|passage=[…] you have that Crooked Wisdome, which is called '''Craft''' […]}}
##* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Jack London}}|title=The Sea-Wolf|year=1904|passage=We have not the strength with which to fight this man; we must dissimulate, and win, if win we can, by '''craft'''.}}
##: {{syn|en|craftiness|cunning|foxiness|guile|slyness|wiliness}}
## {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[occult|Occult]] art, [[magic]] {{defdate|13th century}}.
# {{lb|en|countable|obsolete in the general sense}} A work or [[product]] of art {{defdate|c. 1000}}.
## {{lb|en|collective or plural}} [[handmade|Handmade]] [[items]], especially [[domestic]] or [[decorative]] [[objects]]; handicrafts {{defdate|20th century}}.
##* {{quote-book|en|title=Timberman|date=January 1911|passage=[Canton] has a large export trade in hand-made '''crafts''', ivory and furniture.}}
# {{lb|en|countable|obsolete}} A [[device]], a [[means]]; a [[magical]] device, [[spell]] or [[enchantment]] {{defdate|13th century}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|author=|title=Generydes. A royal historie of the excellent knight Generides|year=c. 1440|passage=For your entente I shall a '''craft''' devise […] That ye shall haue your purpose euery dele.}}
# {{lb|en|countable|obsolete}} [[learning|Learning]] of the schools, [[scholarship]]; a branch of [[learning]] or [[knowledge]], a [[science]], especially one of the ‘seven [[liberal arts]]’ of the [[medieval]] [[university|universities]] {{defdate|13th century}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Cursor Mundi|year=a. 1325|pageurl=https://books.google.de/books?id=Y5NfAAAAcAAJ&dq=%C3%9Ee%20seuen%20craftes%20all%20he%20can&hl=de&pg=PA196#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=272|passage=[…] Þe seuen '''craftes''' all he can […]}}
# {{lb|en|uncountable}} Skill, skilfulness, art, especially the skill needed for a particular [[profession]] {{defdate|9th century}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Ben Jonson}}|title=Timber: or Discoveries made upon Men and Matter |year=1640|pageurl=https://books.google.de/books?id=ZeQVAAAAYAAJ&dq=A%20poem%20is%20the%20work%20of%20the%20poet%3B%20poesy%20is%20his%20skill%20or%20craft%20of%20making.%20jonson&hl=de&pg=PA213#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=213|passage=A poem […] is the work of the poet; the end and fruit of his labour and study. Poesy is his skill or '''craft''' of making; the very fiction itself, the reason or form of the work.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Joseph Moxon}}|title=Mechanick exercises, or The doctrine of handy-works|year=1678|passage=It is counted […] good workmanship in a Joyner, to have the '''craft''' of bearing his hand so curiously even, the whole length of a long Board.}}
#: {{ux|en|The '''craft''' of writing plays.}}
#: {{syn|en|craftsmanship|workmanship}}
# {{lb|en|countable|plural '''crafts'''}} A [[branch]] of skilled [[work]] or [[trade]], especially one requiring [[manual]] dexterity or [[artistic]] skill, but sometimes applied equally to any [[business]], [[calling]] or [[profession]]; the [[skilled]] [[practice]] of a practical [[occupation]] {{defdate|since the 9th century}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Henry Wadsworth Longfellow}}|title=Evangeline, A Tale of Acadie|year=1847|pageurl=https://books.google.de/books?id=ZZk5AQAAMAAJ&dq=Since%20the%20birth%20of%20time%2C%20throughout%20all%20ages%20and%20nations%2C%20Has%20the%20craft%20of%20the%20smith%20been%20held%20in%20repute%20longfellow&hl=de&pg=PA281#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=281|passage=[…] For since the birth of time, throughout all ages and nations, / Has the '''craft''' of the smith been held in repute by the people.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Edward Augustus Freeman}}|title=The history of the Norman conquest|year=1871|pageurl=https://books.google.de/books?id=zlRnAAAAMAAJ&dq=freeman%20Fond%20as%20William%20was%20of%20the%20craft%20of%20the%20woods.%20norman&hl=de&pg=PA250#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=250|passage=Fond as William was of the '''craft''' of the woods, he was the least likely of all men to let his sport stand in the way of his interest.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|James Munson}}|title=The Nonconformists: In Search of a Lost Culture|year=1991|pageurl=https://books.google.de/books?id=epscAAAAMAAJ&q="The+great+preachers+were+masters+of+their+craft"&dq="The+great+preachers+were+masters+of+their+craft"&hl=de&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiXrqf9pNjcAhXEa1AKHQ3RBD8Q6AEIJzAA|page=113|passage=The great preachers were masters of their '''craft'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|The carpenter's '''craft'''.}}
#: {{ux|en|He learned his '''craft''' as an apprentice.}}
#: {{syn|en|art|trade|handicraft|business|profession}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[trade]] or profession as embodied in its practitioners collectively; the [[member]]s of a trade or handicraft as a body; an association of these; a trade's [[union]], [[guild]], or ‘[[company]]’ {{defdate|15th century}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|author={{w|Geoffrey Chaucer}}|title=The Canterbury Tales. The Cokes Tale|year=c. 1386|pageurl=https://books.google.de/books?id=0-sQAAAAYAAJ&dq=Of%20a%20craft%20of%20vitaillers%20was%20he%20chaucer&hl=de&pg=PA50#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=50|passage=A prentis whilom dwelt in our citee, / And of a '''craft''' of vitaillers was he […]}}
#: {{ux|en|She represented the '''craft''' of [[brewer]]s.}}
# {{lb|en|countable|plural '''craft'''}} A [[vehicle]] designed for [[navigation]] in or on [[water]] or [[air]] or through [[outer space]] {{defdate|since the 17th century}}.
## {{lb|en|nautical}} [[boat|Boats]], especially of smaller size than [[ship]]s. Historically primarily applied to [[vessel]]s engaged in loading or unloading of other vessels, as [[lighter]]s, [[hoy]]s, and [[barge]]s.
## {{lb|en|nautical|British Royal Navy}} Those vessels attendant on a [[fleet]], such as [[cutter]]s, [[schooner]]s, and [[gun-boat]]s, generally commanded by [[lieutenant]]s.
## {{lb|en|figurative}} A woman.
##* {{RQ:Chmbrs YngrSt|IX}}
##*: “A tight little '''craft''',” was Austin’s invariable comment on the matron; and she looked it, always trim and trig and smooth of surface like a converted yacht cleared for action.
# {{lb|en|countable|fishing}} [[implement|Implement]]s used in catching [[fish]], such as [[net]], [[line]], or [[hook]]. Modern use primarily in [[whaling]], as in [[harpoon]]s, [[hand-lance]]s, etc. {{defdate|17th century}}.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=a. 1784|chapter=An Act for encouraging and regulating Fiſheries|title=Acts and Laws of the State of Connecticut, in America|author=T. Green|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=ywc4AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA79&dq=craft|page=79|passage=''And whereas the continual Interruption of the Courſe and Paſſage of the Fiſh up the Rivers, by the daily drawing of [[sein|Seins]] and other Fiſh-'''Craft''', tends to prevent their Increaſe,{{...}}'' <!-- [sic] italics -->}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=April 27 1869|author=C. M. Scammon|editor=Edward D. Cope|title=On the Cetaceans of the Western Coast of North America|journal=Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia|volume=21|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=9IEOAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA46&dq=craft|page=46|passage=The whaling '''craft''' consists of harpoons, lances, lines, and sealskin buoys, all of their own workmanship.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=a. 1923|author={{w|Charles Boardman Hawes}}|chapter=A Boy Who Went Whaling|title=The Highest Hit: and Other Selections by Newbery Authors|pageurl=https://books.google.de/books?redir_esc=y&hl=de&id=xZC5QKSqW8UC&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=From+the+mate’s+boat+they+removed%2C+at+his+direction%2C+all+whaling+gear+and+craft+except+the+oars+and+a+single+lance.|publisher=Gareth Stevens Publishing|year_published=2001|isbn=9780836828566|page=47|passage=From the mate’s boat they removed, at his direction, all whaling gear and '''craft''' except the oars and a single lance.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1950|journal=Discovery Reports|volume=26|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=GFgqAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Cambridge University Press|page=318|passage={{...}}Temple, a negro of New Bedford, who made ‘[[whalecraft]]’, that is, was a blacksmith engaged in working from iron the special utensils or ‘'''craft'''’ of the whaling trade.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1991|author=Joan Druett|title=Petticoat Whalers: Whaling Wives at Sea, 1820–1920|publisher=University Press of New England|year_published=2001|isbn=978-1-58465-159-8|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=lwfRQFIeBYMC&pg=PA55&dq=craft|page=55|passage=The men raced about decks collecting the whaling '''craft''' and gear and putting them into the boats, while all the time the lookouts hollered from above.}}

====Usage notes====
The plural ''craft'' is used to refer to vehicles. All other senses use the plural ''crafts''.

