{{also|Patronage}}
==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
From {{inh|en|enm|patronage}}, from {{der|en|fro|patronage}} (modern {{cog|fr|patronage}}). Equivalent to {{suffix|en|patron|age}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/ˈpeɪtɹənɪd͡ʒ/}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-patronage.wav|Audio (UK)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# The act of providing [[approval]] and [[support]]; [[backing]]; [[championship]].
#: {{ux|en|His vigorous '''patronage''' of the conservatives got him in trouble with progressives.}}
# [[customer|Customer]]s [[collectively]]; [[clientele]]; [[business]].
#: {{ux|en|The restaurant had an upper-class '''patronage'''.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year=1961|month=October|title=The winter timetables of British Railways: Western Region|journal=Trains Illustrated|pages=590-591|text=The improved service to and from Taunton is fully justified by the passenger '''patronage''' to and from this town, which is a railhead for a large surrounding area.}}
#: {{hypo|en|ridership}}
# A [[communication]] that indicates lack of [[respect]] by patronizing the [[recipient]]; [[condescension]]; [[disdain]].
# {{lb|en|politics}} Granting [[favour]]s or giving [[contract]]s or making [[appointment]]s to [[office]] in return for [[political]] support.
#* '''2015''', Thomas J. Gradel, Dick Simpson, ''Corrupt Illinois: Patronage, Cronyism, and Criminality'', University of Illinois Press ({{ISBN|9780252097034}}), page 117:
#*: '''Patronage''', nepotism, cronyism, abuse of power, and criminal activity flourish,  sometimes for decades, in numerous town halls, police stations, and special-purpose government agencies in the suburbs.
# [[guardianship|Guardianship]], as of a [[saint]]; [[tutelary]] [[care]].
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Woman and Her Era|author=Eliza Farnham|year=1864|passage=Each of the Arts whose office is to refine, purify, adorn, embellish and grace life is under the '''patronage''' of a Muse, no god being found worthy to preside over them.}}
#: {{rfquotek|en|Addison}}
# The [[right]] of [[nomination]] to [[political]] [[office]].
# {{lb|en|UK|legal}} The [[right]] of [[presentation]] to [[church]] or [[ecclesiastical]] [[benefice]]; [[advowson]].
#* {{RQ:Blackstone Comm|passage=Advowson is the right of presentation to a church, or ecclesiastical benefice. Advowson, advocatio, signifies the taking into protection; and therefore is synonymous with '''patronage'''

