{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To support by being a [[patron]] of.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|author=Hubert Michael Seiwert|title=Popular Religious Movements and Heterodox Sects in Chinese History|published=BRILL|isbn=9789004131460|ur=http://books.google.com/books?id=Xg-gcQq1TGQC&pg=PA62&dq=patronaged|page=62|passage=Mingdi continued the policy of his father who had '''patronaged''' Confucian learning.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2004|author=C.K. Gandhirajan|title=Organized Crime|publisher=APH Publishing Corporation|isbn=978-81-7648-481-7|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=ohyhsmWmelAC&pg=PA147&dq=patronaged|page=147|passage=Table 5.4 reveals the role of criminal gangs’ patron under each crime category. From this, we can understand that 74 percent of the mercenaries are '''patronaged''' and supported by the politicians either of the ruling or opposition party.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2007|author=Stefaan Fiers and Ineke Secker|chapter=6, A Career through the Party|editors=Maurizio Cotta and Heinrich Best|title=Democratic Representation in Europe|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-923420-2|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=EtetpwF-xHMC&pg=PA138&dq=patronaged|page=138|passage=To summarize: a person with a party political background is thus defined as ‘a person that has served in (a) {{...}} and/or (b) a non-elective position inside the party administration of '''patronaged''' position in another organisation, i.e. ''the political functionary''’.}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To be a regular customer or client of; to [[patronize]]
#: {{syn|en|support|keep going}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|year={{circa|1880}}|magazine=The Primary Teacher|volume=3|publisher=New-England Publishing Company|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=sxgVAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA33&dq=patronaged|page=63|passage=This house is largely '''patronaged''' by the professors and students of many of the Educational Institutions of New England and the Middle States; and all perons visiting New York, either for business or pleasure, will find this an excellent place at which to stop.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=May 1902|journal=Oregon Poultry Journal|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=flRMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA27&dq=patronage|page=27|passage=Mr. F. A. Welch, of the Oak View Poultry Farm, Salem, starts an add with us this issue. {{...}} Our readers will be treated well, if they '''patronage''' Mr. Welch.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2002|author=Kevin Fox Gotham|title=Race, Real Estate, and Uneven Development|publisher=SUNY Press|isbn=978-0-7914-5377-3|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=CRG0QOEw9wAC&pg=PA28&dq=patronaged|page=28|passage=Most public establishments catered to Blacks, and Whites actively '''patronaged''' some black-owned businesses (Martin 1982, 6, 9–11; Slingsby 1980, 31–32).}}

