===Etymology 3===
From {{inh|en|enm|dele|t=plank}}, from {{der|en|gml|dele}}, from {{der|en|osx|thili}}, ultimately from {{der|en|gem-pro|*þiljǭ|t=plank, board}}; cognate with {{cog|ang|þille}}. {{doublet|en|thill}}.

====Noun====
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|uncountable}} [[wood|Wood]] that is easy to [[saw]] (from [[conifer]]s such as pine or fir).
#* '''1722''', {{w|Daniel Defoe}}, ''{{w|A Journal of the Plague Year}},'' London: E. Nutt ''et al.,'' p.{{nbsp}}86,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/b30518362/page/86/mode/1up]</sup>
#*: Some Houses were {{...}} entirely lock’d up, the Doors padlockt, the Windows and Doors having '''Deal''' Boards nail’d over them,
#* {{quote-book|1=en|year=1926|author=Sir Arthur Conan Doyle|authorlink=Arthur Conan Doyle|title=The Land of Mist|url=http://gutenberg.net.au/ebooks06/0601351h.html|passage=A brisk fire burned in the grate, there were three comfortable chairs, and a '''deal''' table with a water carafe, a bucket of coals, and a few other amenities.}}
# {{lb|en|countable}} A [[plank]] of [[softwood]] (fir or pine board).
# {{lb|en|countable|archaic}} A wooden board or plank, usually between 12 or 14 feet in length, traded as a commodity in shipbuilding.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1819|title=Practical abridgement of the laws of customs and excise|author=Charles Pope|edition=5th|page=CCXLIII|passage=It shall not be lawful for any person to land any timber, planks or board, '''deals''', staves, tar, pitch, turpentine, rozin or other the commodities aforesaid, on any part of the present quays within the city of Bristol, from any vessel coming into the said port...}}
#* {{quote-book|en|title=A Dictionary Practical, Theoretical and Historical of Commerce and Commercial Navigation|author=John Ramsey McCulloch|chapter=Docks on the Thames (London)|page=590|passage=Swedish '''deals''' from ports in the Baltic|vol=1|year=1840|publisher=Thomas Wardle}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2003|author=François Cardarelli|page=52|title=Encyclopaedia of Scientific Units, Weights, and Measures|passage=1 '''deal''' (US) = 12 ft x 11 in. x 3/2 in. (E)}}

