==English==

===Etymology===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*dewk-}}
Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|prōductus}}, perfect participle of {{m|la|prōdūcō}}, first attested in English in the mathematics sense.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|en|/ˈpɹɒd.əkt/|/ˈpɹɒd.ʌkt/}}
* {{a|GA}} {{enPR|prŏd′əkt}}, {{IPA|en|/ˈpɹɑd.əkt/|/ˈpɹɑd.ʌkt/}}
* {{hyph|en|prod|uct}}
* {{audio|en|En-us-product.ogg|Audio (USA)}}
* {{rhymes|en|ʌkt}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|~}}

# {{lb|en|countable|uncountable}} A [[commodity]] offered for sale.
#: {{ux|en|That store offers a variety of '''products'''.&emsp; We've got to sell a lot of '''product''' by the end of the month.}}
#: {{syn|en|merchandise|wares|goods}}
# {{lb|en|cosmetics|uncountable}} Any preparation to be applied to the hair, skin, nails, etc.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2020|author=[[w:Brandon Taylor (writer)|Brandon Taylor]]|title=[[w:Real Life (novel)|Real Life]]|publisher=Daunt Books Originals|page=153|passage=He puts his fingers in Miller’s hair, which is greasy with '''product'''. }}
#: {{ux|en|Wash excess '''product''' out of your hair.}}
# Anything that is produced; a [[result]].
#: {{ux|en|The '''product''' of last month's quality standards committee is quite good, even though the process was flawed.}}
#* {{RQ:Milton Paradise Lost|XI|To whom thus Michael: These are the '''product''' / Of those ill-mated marriages thou sawest;|lines=683-84}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1790|{{w|Edmund Burke}}|{{w|Reflections on the Revolution in France}}|passage=These institutions are the '''products''' of enthusiasm; they are the instruments of wisdom.}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2014-06-21|volume=411|issue=8892|magazine={{w|The Economist}}
|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/books-and-arts/21604535-real-sir-isaac-newton-was-not-first-king-reason-last Magician’s brain]
|passage=The truth is that [Isaac] Newton was very much a '''product''' of his time. The colossus of science was not the first king of reason, Keynes wrote after reading Newton’s unpublished manuscripts. Instead “he was the last of the magicians”.}}
## The amount of an artifact that has been created by someone or some process.
##: {{ux|en|They improve their '''product''' every year; they export most of their agricultural production.}}
##: {{syn|en|endwork|production|output|creation|yield}}
## A consequence of someone's efforts or of a particular set of circumstances.
##: {{ux|en|Skill is the '''product''' of hours of practice.&emsp; His reaction was the '''product''' of hunger and fatigue.}}
## {{lb|en|chemistry}} A chemical substance formed as a result of a chemical reaction.
##: {{ux|en|This is a '''product''' of lime and nitric acid.}}
## {{senseid|en|multiplication}}{{lb|en|arithmetic}} A quantity obtained by multiplication of two or more numbers.
##: {{ux|en|The '''product''' of 2 and 3 is 6.&emsp; The '''product''' of 2, 3, and 4 is 24.}}
## {{lb|en|mathematics}} Any operation or a result thereof which generalises multiplication of numbers, like the [[multiplicative operation]] in a [[ring]], [[product type|product of types]] or a [[categorical product]].
## Any tangible or intangible good or service that is a result of a process and that is intended for delivery to a customer or end user.
##* {{quote-book|en|title=The future of retail banking in Europe|page=146|author=Oonagh McDonald|coauthors=Kevin Keasey|year=2002|passage=Product innovation is needed to meet changes in society and its requirements for particular types of banking '''product'''.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|title=E-business and e-challenges|page=133|author=Veljko Milutinović|coauthors=Frédéric Patricelli|year=2002|passage=This sort of relationship can improve quality of transportation and can help in negotiations between transportation providers and transportation '''product''' users.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|title=Software project management for dummies|page=55|author=Teresa Luckey|coauthors=Joseph Phillips|year=2006|passage=You can't create a stellar software '''product''' unless you know what it is supposed to do. You must work with the stakeholders to create the '''product''' scope.}}
# {{lb|en|US|slang}} Illegal drugs, especially cocaine, when viewed as a commodity.
#: {{ux|en|I got some '''product''' here – you buying?}}

