===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|intransitive|archaic}} To [[compose]] [[fables]]; hence, to write or speak [[fiction]]; to write or [[utter]] what is not true.
#* '''1591''', {{w|William Shakespeare}}, ''{{w|Henry VI, Part 1}}'', Act IV, Scene 2,<sup>[http://www.opensourceshakespeare.org/views/plays/play_view.php?WorkID=henry6p1&Scope=entire&pleasewait=1&msg=pl]</sup>
#*: He '''fables''' not; I hear the enemy:
#*: Out, some light horsemen, and peruse their wings.
#* '''1706''', {{w|Matthew Prior}}, “An Ode, Humbly Inscribed to the Queen,” stanza 17, in {{w|Samuel Johnson}} (editor), ''The Works of the English Poets'', London, 1779, Volume 30, p. 254,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/worksenglishpoe13johngoog]</sup>
#*: Vain now the tales which '''fabling''' poets tell,
#*: That wavering Conquest still desires to rove!
#*: In [[w:John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough|Marlborough]]’s camp the goddess knows to dwell:
#*: Long as the hero’s life remains her love.
#* '''1852''', {{w|Matthew Arnold}}, ''Empedocles on Etna'', Act II, in ''Empedocles on Etna and Other Poems'', London: B. Fellowes, p. 50,<sup>[https://archive.org/details/empedoclesonetna00arno]</sup>
#*: He '''fables''', yet speaks truth.
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic}} To [[make up]]; to [[devise]], and speak of, as true or real; to tell of [[falsely]]; to [[recount]] in the form of a fable.
#* '''1674''', [[w:John Milton|John Milton]], ''{{w|Paradise Lost}}'', Book VI, lines 288-292,<sup>[https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Paradise_Lost_(1674)/Book_VI]</sup>
#*: {{...}} err not, that so shall end
#*: The strife which thou callest evil, but we style
#*: The strife of glory; which we mean to win,
#*: Or turn this Heaven itself into the Hell
#*: Thou '''fablest''' {{...}}
#* '''1691''', {{w|Arthur Gorges}} (translator), ''The Wisdom of the Ancients'' by {{w|Francis Bacon}} (1609), London, “Cassandra, or, Divination,” <sup>[https://archive.org/details/fessaysorcounsel00baco]</sup>
#*: The ''Poets'' '''Fable''', That ''Apollo'' being enamoured of ''Cassandra'', was by her many shifts and cunning slights still deluded in his Desire {{...}}
#* '''1922''', [[w:James Joyce|James Joyce]], ''{{w|Ulysses}}'', Chapter II,<sup>[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/4300/4300-h/4300-h.htm#chap02]</sup>
#*: '''Fabled''' by the daughters of memory. And yet it was in some way if not as memory '''fabled''' it. A phrase, then, of impatience, thud of Blake’s wings of excess.{{...}}
#: {{syn|en|make up|invent|feign|devise}}

