==Norwegian Bokmål==
{{wp|lang=nb|Abacá}}
[[File:AmCyc Manila Hemp.jpg|200px|thumb|'''abaca''' ({{taxlink|Musa textilis|species|noshow=1}})]]

===Etymology===
From {{der|nb|en|abaca}}, from {{der|nb|es|abacá||abaca}}, from {{der|nb|tl|abaká||abaca}}, from {{der|nb|ar|أَبَق||abaca}}, from {{der|nb|syc|ܐܳܦܰܩܬܳܐ|tr=ʾāpaqtā}}, {{m|syc|ܐܰܦܩܰܥܬܳܐ|tr=ʾap̄qaʿtā||de-seeded cotton}} from {{m|syc|ܦܩܰܥ|tr=pqaʿ||to split, to reave, to crack}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|nb|/aˈbɑːka/}}
* {{audio|nb|NB - Pronunciation of Norwegian Bokmål «abaca».ogg|Audio}}
* {{rhymes|nb|ɑːka}}
* {{hyph|nb|a|ba|ca}}

===Noun===
{{nb-noun-m1}} 

# {{lb|nb|botany}} {{taxlink|Musa textilis|species|noshow=1|ver=161026}}, a species of [[banana]] tree native to the [[Philippines]] grown for its textile, rope- and [[papermaking]] fibre.
# {{l|nb|abaca}} {{q|the fiber of the {{l|en|abaca}} plant, used in rope}}
#: {{syn|nb|manilahamp}}

