[[Category:nb:Plants]]

==English==
{{wikipedia}}

===Etymology===
From {{der|en|LL.|abacinātus}}, perfect passive participle of {{m|la|abacinō}}; possibly formed from {{m|la|ab||off}} + {{m|la|bacīnum||a basin}} or {{m|la|bacīnus}}. Probably cognate with modern Italian {{m|it|abbacinare||to dazzle}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|En-uk-abacinate.ogg|Audio (UK)}}
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/æbˈæsɪneɪt/}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive|rare}} To [[blind]] by holding a [[red-hot]] metal rod or plate before the eyes
#* {{quote-book|en|1905|James M. Ludlow|Sir Raoul|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=kXEmmDGmYdEC&q=%22not+of+hot+irons+but%22|page=233
|passage="You young scapegrace," said Dandolo, "I will myself '''abacinate''' you — in the Venetian way." "How's that?" "Blind your eyes with the glare, not of hot irons, but of new ducats. Count your pile."}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1945|Robert Hardy Andrews|Burning Gold|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=v-58AAAAMAAJ|page=196
|passage=Their straining eyes '''abacinated''' by the cup of terror, their throats stopped, their powers dead within them, they hung breathless, motionless.}}
#* {{quote-song|1=en|author=Jeff Hanneman|year=1986|artist=Slayer|title=Angel of Death|url=|album=Reign in Blood|text='''Abacinate''', eyes that bleed, praying for the end of your wide awake nightmare.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1999|Srinivas Aravamudan|Tropicopolitans|page=220|pageurl=http://books.google.com/books?id=17oU9nBX_N8C&pg=PA220|isbn=082232315X
|passage=This chiasmic image of the subject's imperviousness suggests a sensory deprivation beyond sublimity, like that of '''abacinated''' anti-epistemology.}}

====Derived terms====
* {{l|en|abacination}}

